<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,611,1653]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,1545,1571]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is very close to 
<taxonomicName box="[706,882,1546,1571]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vertebratus">
<emphasis box="[706,882,1546,1571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">D. vertebratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in having a black scutum and a predominantly black abdomen; the costal band apical spot starts abruptly from a parallel sided portion of the costal band that extends beyond vein R 
<number box="[610,618,1639,1653]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[628,635,1639,1653]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
; in 
<taxonomicName box="[680,849,1623,1648]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vertebratus">
<emphasis box="[680,849,1623,1648]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">D. vertebratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the spot starts more gradually.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
